<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<chapter subject="Mathematics" id="114" name="Principle of Mathematical Induction">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Mathematical induction is a technique used to prove ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Statements for all natural numbers</option><option id="B">Negative integers only</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Usually denoted as P(n).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The first step in induction is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Basis step</option><option id="B">Inductive step</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Verification for n = 1 (or starting value).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The assumption that P(k) is true for some natural number k is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Inductive hypothesis</option><option id="B">Proof</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used to bridge to P(k+1).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In the Basis step, we usually check P(n) for n = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1</option><option id="B">0 always</option><option id="C">-1</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Smallest natural number.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mathematical Induction works like a row of falling ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dominoes</option><option id="B">Cards</option><option id="C">Bricks</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard analogy for sequential truth.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If P(k) implies P(k+1) is true, it is the ____ step.</text>
            <option id="A">Inductive</option><option id="B">Basis</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Heart of the induction proof.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sum of first n natural numbers is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">n(n+1)/2</option><option id="B">n^2</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proven by induction easily.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sum of first n odd natural numbers is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">n^2</option><option id="B">n(n+1)</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sequence 1, 3, 5...</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sum of first n even natural numbers is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">n(n+1)</option><option id="B">n^2</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sequence 2, 4, 6...</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Induction is fundamentally based on ____ set.</text>
            <option id="A">Natural numbers N</option><option id="B">Real numbers R</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Discrete well-ordered set.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The 'n' in P(n) must be an ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Integer / Natural number</option><option id="B">Fraction</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cannot apply to continuous variables directly.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If P(1) is true and P(k) -&gt; P(k+1) for all k, then P(n) is true for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">All n in N</option><option id="B">Only odd n</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Final conclusion of induction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Inductive hypothesis assumes P(k) is true for ____ k.</text>
            <option id="A">Some / Arbitrary</option><option id="B">All</option><option id="C">No</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>We don't know it's always true yet.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Can induction be used for inequalities?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Very common application.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sum of squares of first n natural numbers is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">n(n+1)(2n+1)/6</option><option id="B">n^2(n+1)^2/4</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard formula.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sum of cubes of first n natural numbers is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">[n(n+1)/2]^2</option><option id="B">n^3</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Equals square of sum of first n numbers.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>For a statement to be proved by induction, it must be ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Generalizable</option><option id="B">Negative</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Must depend on n.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Basis step for n &gt;= 4 starts with verifying P(____).</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Match the range provided.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>1 + 2 + 2^2 + ... + 2^(n-1) = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2^n - 1</option><option id="B">2^(n+1)</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Geometric progression sum.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Product (1+1/1)(1+1/2)...(1+1/n) = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">n + 1</option><option id="B">n</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Telescoping product.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>3^(2n) - 1 is always divisible by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">8</option><option id="B">5</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Check for n=1: 9-1=8.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>n(n+1)(n+5) is always multiple of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">3</option><option id="B">7</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Divisibility induction application.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If n^2 &lt; 2^n for n &gt;= ____.</text>
            <option id="A">5</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">10</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Check n=4: 16 &lt; 16 (False). n=5: 25 &lt; 32 (True).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>2^(3n) - 1 is divisible by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">7</option><option id="B">9</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Check n=1: 8-1=7.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>10^(2n-1) + 1 is divisible by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">11</option><option id="B">13</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Check n=1: 10^1 + 1 = 11.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sum of angles of n-sided polygon is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(n-2) x 180</option><option id="B">(n-1) x 90</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proven by induction starting n=3.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>n! &gt; 2^n is true for n &gt;= ____.</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Check n=3: 6 &gt; 8 (F). n=4: 24 &gt; 16 (T).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is 7^n - 3^n divisible by 4?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>x^n - y^n is divisible by x-y.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Principle of Mathematical Induction is also called principle of ____ induction.</text>
            <option id="A">Finite</option><option id="B">Infinite</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used for discrete counts.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>To prove P(k+1), we use the ____ of P(k).</text>
            <option id="A">Truth / Assumption</option><option id="B">Falsehood</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Bridge step.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Induction can prove 'A implies B' for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sequences of implications</option><option id="B">Single numbers</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Iterative logic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A set is well-ordered if every non-empty subset has a ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Least element</option><option id="B">Max element</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Foundation of induction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Does induction work for negative integers?</text>
            <option id="A">Only if we shift the index (redefine m = n + c)</option><option id="B">No, jamais</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Adaptable by mapping to N.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The inductive step must be true for ____ k.</text>
            <option id="A">Every k &gt;= start value</option><option id="B">Some k</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Must not break the chain.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If basis step fails, can the statement be true for all n?</text>
            <option id="A">No</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>First domino must fall.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Strong induction assumes truth of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">P(1), P(2) ... P(k)</option><option id="B">Only P(k)</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Useful for proofs involving recursion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sum of 1 + 3 + 5 + ... + (2n-1) = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">n^2</option><option id="B">2n^2</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard odd sum.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>1/1.2 + 1/2.3 + ... + 1/n(n+1) = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">n / (n+1)</option><option id="B">1 / n</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Telescoping series sum.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Induction can be applied in ____ geometry?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (e.g. number of diagonals)</option><option id="B">No, only algebra</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used for n-sided shapes properties.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A property P(n) is valid if it holds for n=1 and P(k) -&gt; P(k+1).</text>
            <option id="A">True</option><option id="B">False</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Definition of PMI.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Prove n &lt; 2^n for all natural numbers n. Basis check n=1:</text>
            <option id="A">1 &lt; 2 (True)</option><option id="B">1 &lt; 1</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Basic exponential inequality.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>n^3 - n is multiple of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">6</option><option id="B">5</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>n(n-1)(n+1) - product of 3 consecutive integers.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>x^n - y^n is always divisible by (x-y) for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">All natural n</option><option id="B">Even n only</option><option id="C">Odd n only</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard algebraic identity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>x^n + y^n is divisible by (x+y) for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Odd natural n</option><option id="B">Even natural n</option><option id="C">All n</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Check n=2: x^2+y^2 not div by x+y.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bernoulli's Inequality: (1+x)^n &gt;= ____ for x &gt; -1.</text>
            <option id="A">1 + nx</option><option id="B">1 + x^n</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>True for all n in N.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sum 1.2 + 2.3 + 3.4 + ... + n(n+1) = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">n(n+1)(n+2)/3</option><option id="B">n(n+1)/2</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proven by induction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>n(n^2 + 5) is divisible by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">6</option><option id="B">4</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Check n=1: 6, n=2: 18. Both div by 6.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>2.7^n + 3.5^n - 5 is divisible by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">24</option><option id="B">12</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Complex divisibility induction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Product of three consecutive natural numbers is divisible by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">6</option><option id="B">3</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>3! = 6.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of subsets of set with n elements is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2^n</option><option id="B">n^2</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proven by induction on n.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Induction can prove results about finite sets? Yes, on their ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cardinality n</option><option id="B">Colors</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mapped to integers.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>10^n + 3.4^(n+2) + 5 is div by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">9</option><option id="B">7</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Divisibility check application.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>For P(k) -&gt; P(k+1) to be proven, we start with LHS of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">P(k+1)</option><option id="B">P(k)</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Substitute the hypothesis into the k-terms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>1.3 + 2.3^2 + ... + n.3^n = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(2n-1)3^(n+1) + 3 / 4</option><option id="B">3^n</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Arithmetico-geometric series sum.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Can we start induction from n=0?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes, if statement applies to n=0</option><option id="B">No, jamais</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Basis step index is adjustable.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Wait till n=3 for n^2 &lt; 2^n? No, 2&lt;4, 9&lt;8 (F). Start n=5.</text>
            <option id="A">n=5</option><option id="B">n=1</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Careful verification of start point.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>n^7 - n is always div by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">7</option><option id="B">5</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fermat's little theorem special case n=7.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sum of (2k - 1)^2 for k=1 to n = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">n(4n^2 - 1)/3</option><option id="B">n^3</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Squares of odd numbers.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sum 1.3 + 3.5 + 5.7 + ... to n terms = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">n(4n^2 + 6n - 1)/3</option><option id="B">n^3</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Product of odd numbers sum.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Inverse of induction proof: assuming P(k+1) true, show P(k)? No. That's not PMI.</text>
            <option id="A">True</option><option id="B">False</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Order of implication is k to k+1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If S is set of natural numbers and 1 in S, k in S -&gt; k+1 in S, then ____.</text>
            <option id="A">S = N</option><option id="B">S is finite</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Peano's axiom / PMI axiom.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Derivative d/dx (x^n) = n x^(n-1) proven by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Induction</option><option id="B">Observation</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Using product rule and k to k+1 shift.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>De Moivre's Theorem: (cos A + i sin A)^n = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">cos nA + i sin nA</option><option id="B">cos^n A</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proven by induction on n.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Power Set of set with n elements has size 2^n. Induction starts at n=____?</text>
            <option id="A">0 (Empty set has 1 subset)</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Works for zero too.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is 2^(3n) - 7n - 1 divisible by 49?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Classic induction problem.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Difference (2n+7) &lt; (n+3)^2 for all n in N?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Check n=1: 9 &lt; 16. True.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>1^2 + 2^2 + ... + n^2 is O(n^3)?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Asymptotic analysis link.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A statement P(n) holds for all odd n if P(1) true and P(k) -&gt; P(k+2)?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Skipped induction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is induction a form of deductive reasoning or inductive reasoning? Despite name...</text>
            <option id="A">Deductive</option><option id="B">Inductive</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>It's a rigorous deduction from axioms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>4^n - 3n - 1 is multiple of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">9</option><option id="B">7</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Check n=1: 4-3-1=0. n=2: 16-6-1=9.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Inductive step P(k) assumes truth. Is it circular reasoning?</text>
            <option id="A">No (It proves conditional P(k)-&gt;P(k+1))</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Logical validity of conditional.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Limit of induction: cannot prove for all Real numbers x directly?</text>
            <option id="A">True</option><option id="B">False</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>R is not well-ordered like N.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>n-th harmonic number H_n sum 1 + 1/2 + ... + 1/n. Is H_(2^n) &gt;= 1 + n/2?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Classic inequality induction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of diagonals in n-sided convex polygon is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">n(n-3)/2</option><option id="B">n(n-1)/2</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proven starting n=3.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>2.3^n - 1 is divisible by 5? Check n=1: 6-1=5.</text>
            <option id="A">Only for n=odd? No, n=any.</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Verification leads to proof.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Induction on n for sum of first n terms of AP: a + (a+d) + ... is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(n/2)[2a + (n-1)d]</option><option id="B">n/2 (a+l)</option><option id="C">Both</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fundamental AP formula.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Induction on n for sum of GP a + ar + ... is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">a(r^n - 1) / (r-1)</option><option id="B">a r^n</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fundamental GP formula.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Fibonacci relation F_n: sum of first n numbers is F_(n+2) - 1?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proven by induction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is 41^n - 14^n divisible by 27?</text>
